<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1927-12-01T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1927-12-01T05:00:00-05:00" n="494" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d494">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.512/721: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Mayer</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1927-12-01T18:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">December 1,
                                        1927—6 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received December 1—10:51
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>1055. 1. Following from consul general at Shanghai: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“November 29, 5 p.m.</p>
                                <list>
                                    <label>(1)</label>
                                    <item>The director of the Surtax Revenue Department, acting
                                        under instructions from the Ministry of Finance, Nanking,
                                        notifies today that on December 1, 1927, he will collect,
                                        apart from the transit dues, a surtax an additional one-half
                                        of the present customs transit dues.</item>
                                    <label>(2)</label>
                                    <item>Shall I file protest or take other action?”</item>
                                </list></quote></p>
                        <pb facs="0536" n="428" xml:id="pg_428"/>
                        <p>2. Department’s instructions requested as to whether Cunningham should
                            protest this apparent extension of the transit dues of Washington
                            Conference surtaxes. I respectfully suggest protesting this unwarranted
                            application of Washington Conference principle in respect of customs
                            dues.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Mayer</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>